A nice exercise to search for Collared in so many Orientals. It was tough but fun and with new practical learning. Classic case of what we know from literature as opposed to what our eyes see in the field.  Once the eyes got trained on seeing Orientals, the subtly different Collared started standing out as an odd man out. Less taller stature, more horizontal stance, clear and apparent tail streamers reaching the tail tips, paler lores than Oriental, a cleaner graduated breast coloration than rufous-brown of Oriental, easily seen wires of the tail in flight, hint of white near secondaries when perched and visually apparent white trailing edge of secondaries when seen in flight, the rufous underwing patch reaching and covering axillaries - were the separators from Orientals.  Behaviour - At ease but aware of movements. Gave calls intermittently and in flight. Kept distance. It did lie down in the ground depressions once in a while; unsure whether this was to hide or rest but we didn't notice the same in case of Oriental.

Conservative estimate from the patch birded and based on the visually identifiable distance. Counted by noting the clusters of individuals containing roughly 6 birds and then noting them in 4 patches. Rounded the number considering birds flushed and in flight.

Observation Details: After scanning and waiting for long time, in the crazy heat of April, finally managed to see a pair. It was later joined by 2 more individuals. At one instance, saw all 4 flying to a tall tree in quick succession while a single individual was vocalizing from opposite direction. Could not see this one though.  2+2+1 Managed a record shot of a pair.

A male calling after certain intervals. We tried locating it and inadvertently flushed a female from close by, saw it well in flight and then perched deep within the forest. Male kept calling but we couldn't locate due to thick vegetation.

Lovely bird! Fortunate to see single individual hunting for flies and butterflies before joined by 2 others. Together, they vocalized, hunted and often kept close to one another - each following the leader tree after tree. Lost their sight after they flew into thick vegetation. Recorded and photographed.
